      <section eId="section_2">
        <heading><b>THE BURIAL (MANAGEMENT) (SCOTLAND) REGULATIONS 2025</b></heading>
        <content />
      </section>
      <section eId="section_3">
        <heading><b>THE BURIAL (APPLICATIONS AND REGISTER) (SCOTLAND) REGULATIONS 2024</b></heading>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Business and Regulatory Impact Assessment</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_4">
        <num><b>1.</b></num>
        <heading>Section 1 Background, aims and options</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Section 1: Background, aims and options</b></p>
        </intro>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>This Business and Regulatory Impact Assessment (BRIA) analyses the cost and benefits to businesses and the third sector of the proposed Burial Management (Scotland) Regulations 2025 and The Burial (Applications and Register) (Scotland) Regulations 2024 to be made under sections 6, 8 and 10 of the Burial and Cremation (Scotland) Act 2016 (‘the 2016 Act’). </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_5">
        <heading>Background to policy issue</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The 2016 Act received Royal Assent in April 2016. It provides a comprehensive legislative framework for burial, cremation and funeral arrangements in Scotland, repealing various pieces of antiquated legislation. The BRIA for the Burial and Cremation (Scotland) Bill was published in October 2015. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The development of the 2016 Act is grounded in the findings and recommendations of a number of important reports including the Burial and Cremation Review Group (2007) chaired by Sheriff Brodie, the Report of the Infant Cremation Commission (2014) chaired by Lord Bonomy and Dame Eilish Angiolini’s findings in the report of the National Cremation Investigation (2016). The 2014 and 2016 reports followed investigations into the variation in retrieval of ashes at different crematoriums from the remains of infants and pregnancy losses cremated in Scotland.  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Scottish Government accepted the recommendations presented in these reports<authorialNote marker="1"><p> See Scottish Government Response to Infant Cremation Commission, which accepts all recommendations without reservation - https://www.gov.scot/publications/scottish-government-response-report-infant-cremation-commission/.</p></authorialNote>, and many of the 2016 Act’s provisions are rooted in their recommendations. For example, recommendation 9 of the Burial and Cremation Review Group stated that all extant legislation should be repealed and consolidated into a single Act with powers to make subordinate legislation as and when necessary. Additionally, recommendation 13.13 of the Infant Cremation Commission stated that the Scottish Ministers should keep the cremation and the funeral industry under review and should consider whether further regulation of either is required. The 2016 Act contains various powers to make regulations to regulate the burial, cremation and funeral director sectors. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_6">
        <heading>The Scottish Government made The Burial and Cremation (Pregnancy Loss Prescribed Information and Forms) (Scotland) Regulations 2018 to make provision for the arrangements for burial or cremation following a pregnancy loss or stillbirth, which came into force on 4 April 2019. The Cremation (Scotland) Regulations 2019 (‘the 2019 Regulations’), also came into force on 4 April 2019 and provide the statutory framework for the management and operation of crematoriums, applications for cremation, handling of ashes, etc.</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The 2016 Act also provides powers for the Scottish Ministers to create codes of practice for funeral directors (section 97), burial (section 21) and cremation (section 64), appoint inspectors of the burial, cremation and funeral director sectors (section 89) and create a licensing scheme for funeral directors’ businesses (section 95). The Funeral Director Code of Practice which was passed by the Scottish Parliament in January 2024 and comes into force in March 2025.  All funeral directors will be required to comply with the Code.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_7">
        <heading>The burial regulations</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Prior to the 2016 Act, the law on burial was patchwork; a mix of old legislation and common law which had not been substantially revised or amended since the nineteenth century. Some legislation applied only to local authorities and not private burial authorities. The 2016 Act applies to all burial authorities in order to create consistency across the sector. Amongst other things, the Act sets out a local authority’s duty to provide a burial ground, allows a burial authority to sell the right to erect a building in a burial ground, introduces offences for unauthorised burials and sets out particular circumstances in which a burial authority must sell a right of burial. It also  allows for the Scottish Ministers to make regulations to further regulate specific aspects of burials including  the management, regulation and control by a burial authority of burial grounds, and applications for burials.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>This BRIA assesses the business and regulatory impacts of the following:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <intro>
              <p>The Burial (Management) (Scotland) Regulations 2025 (“The Burial Management Regulations”), which will include: </p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A requirement to create a publicly accessible management plan, with annual review. Management plans aim to increase transparency around how a burial authority operates, how it provides burial services, contingency planning and the maintenance of burial grounds.</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A duty on burial authorities to keep burial grounds in good order and clarity on the powers that burial authorities have to manage their burial grounds (for example, to maintain and repair walls, buildings and fences, maintain or improve access to the burial ground, alter the surface of lairs, manage vegetation etc.) </p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A requirement to carry out regular, scheduled inspections of headstones and memorials to ensure they are in safe order</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>The power to remove unauthorised headstones or memorials</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A requirement for staff to be trained in the use of burial equipment and to keep a written record of training </p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A power to designate areas of a burial ground for use by particular faith, religion or belief groups. </p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <intro>
              <p>The Burial (Applications and Register) (Scotland) Regulations 2024 (“The Burial Applications and Register Regulations”), which will include:</p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>The introduction of standard statutory burial forms and prescribed information to be included in burial registers, to be used by all burial authorities for all burials in Scotland, replacing locally produced forms;</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A requirement to submit accompanying documents with burial applications;</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>Identifies those who may submit a burial application form;</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>◦</num>
              <content>
                <p>A requirement for burial authorities to keep a record of all burial applications for 50 years from the date of burial</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>In this assessment, the above two sets of regulations will be referred to collectively as “the burial regulations”</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_8">
        <heading>Purpose/ aim of action and desired effect</heading>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_9">
        <heading>Objective</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The objective of the burial regulations is to improve, clarify and streamline burial processes and record-keeping across all of Scotland’s burial authorities. This ensures authorities are clear on the extent of their powers and the actions they can take. In doing so, the burial regulations will contribute to the wider regulatory regime aimed at protecting the deceased and bereaved, setting minimum standards for the sector and supporting consistency of service. In this way, we aim to provide the public with greater confidence in the burial sector in Scotland and promote ongoing improvement.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Whilst burial regulations will set out a baseline set of requirements, it is intended that these will later be accompanied by a Burial Code of Practice (as provided for under section 21 of the 2016 Act). </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>This BRIA will be used to analyse the costs and benefits of the burial regulations to businesses and the third sector. Through all stages of regulation development, evaluation of the evidence and extensive consultation with those with expert knowledge has helped to identify the proposal that best achieves the policy objectives while minimising the costs and burdens as much as possible.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_10">
        <heading>Rationale for Government intervention</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Legislative responsibility and commitment to implement recommendations </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Burial and Cremation Review Group (“the Group”) was established in 2005 and published its report and recommendations in October 2007. It made recommendations on how the law relating to burial and cremation could be changed in order to better serve the needs of the people of Scotland. At this time, the legislation around burial had not been substantially revised or amended since the nineteenth century. The Group recognised the lack of general regulations governing the management of burial grounds in Scotland which, at times, causes difficulties for burial ground managers – especially in regard to powers to take positive action to address unsafe or abandoned memorials. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The 2016 Act repealed the antiquated primary and secondary legislation and replaced it with consolidated legislation covering burial and cremation, as well as funeral directors. The Act also provided for the regulation of other methods of body disposal. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations are key to realising the necessary detail, protection and processes envisaged by Part 1 of the 2016 Act. Part 1 is focussed on burial. It will ensure that the right policies and procedures are in place to enable improvements and clarity in the burial sector and provide a set of baseline requirements for inspection and enforcement under the new inspection regime that will be established by the Burial and Cremation (Inspection) (Scotland) Regulations 2025.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>National Strategy for Economic Transformation</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>With respect to Scotland’s National Strategy for Economic Transformation, the burial regulations will contribute in particular to the aim of establishing a culture of delivery and accountability in which objectives are shared and responsibilities are clearly allocated and accepted across the public and private sectors. The modernisation of the legal framework for burial in Scotland has been achieved in close collaboration with the funeral sector to ensure that any statutory requirements are appropriate, well-evidenced and fit for purpose. Such collaboration has ensured the sector has developed a sense of ownership over, and have accepted accountability for, ensuring their compliance with these requirements.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>National Performance Framework</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations do not fit neatly into any particular vision within the National Performance Framework, but they do touch on a number of the outcomes. The regulations aim to make a contribution to the <i>communities outcome</i>. Burial grounds are important local green spaces which hold cultural and historical significance for communities. The burial regulations aim to support burial authorities to manage burial grounds for the benefit of the local communities they serve. The <i>fair work and business outcome</i> is also relevant, with regulations aiming to increase transparency, accountability and provide nationally consistent practices. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_11">
        <heading>Public expectation</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>A public consultation on burial regulations ran from August to November 2023. The proposals in the consultation received a positive response, with respondents welcoming efforts to ensure that burial legislation is fit for purpose both now and in the future. More details on this are set out under the ‘consultation’ section below. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_12">
        <heading>Scope</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations will apply to all burial authorities in Scotland. The burial regulations will be statutory and it is intended that burial authorities must comply with them where they set requirements. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>In the 2016 Act, <span style="color:#1E1E1E">“</span><span style="color:#1E1E1E">burial authority</span><span style="color:#1E1E1E">”, in relation to a burial ground, means the person having responsibility for the management of the burial ground. A “burial ground” - </span></heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>(a)</num>
            <intro>
              <p>means land—</p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>(i)</num>
              <content>
                <p>used, or intended to be used, primarily for the burial of human remains, and</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>(ii)</num>
              <content>
                <p>in respect of which a charge for such burials is made, and</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>(b)</num>
            <intro>
              <p>includes land that was, but is no longer, used primarily for the burial of human remains and that—</p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>(i)</num>
              <content>
                <p>was provided for that purpose in pursuance of a function conferred by an enactment or an obligation imposed by rule of law, or</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
            <subparagraph>
              <num>(ii)</num>
              <content>
                <p>is specified in regulations made by the Scottish Ministers.</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The scope of the sector is set out in greater detail below under “Sectors and Groups Affected”. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_13">
        <heading>Forthcoming related regulations</heading>
        <level>
          <heading>In parallel to the implementation of the proposed burial regulations, the Scottish Government is now progressing the development and implementation of the following:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>inspection regulations, which provide for an inspection regime for burial authorities, cremation authorities and funeral directors under section 90 of the 2016 Act and will be laid in Parliament at the same time as the burial regulations,</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>the funeral director licensing scheme under section 95 of the 2016 Act, and</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>regulations for alkaline hydrolysis (‘water cremation’) as an alternative to burial or cremation, under section 99 of the 2016 Act. The aim is to lay the funeral director licensing and alkaline hydrolysis regulations in 2025/26.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The collection of four public consultations published on the Scottish Government Citizen Space website between August to November 2023 sought views on the proposed burial regulations and proposals for the above listed regulations. Separate BRIAs will be developed for each of these sets of regulations.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_14">
        <heading>Options</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Table 1 (Annex) sets out in full the options considered and the recommended approach for each discrete area of the burial regulations. The assessment and final recommendation for each part has been informed by the views of representatives of the consulted businesses and authorities to capture the industry’s preferred options.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The options reported in this section of the BRIA relate to the overarching approach to introducing the burial regulations and the resulting impact on burial authorities (public and private businesses) and funeral directors (private businesses).</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The financial implications of complying with the options set out here and in the Annex below are not easily quantifiable but any direct or indirect financial costs are considered minimal. They involve procedural and administrative changes which do not require significant resource allocation or investment. e.g. the burial regulations do not require businesses to invest in new equipment and do not impact revenue or profit. Non-monetary ‘costs’ are reported below.  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_15">
        <heading><b>Option A – Do nothing</b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Maintaining the status quo would mean that burial policy in Scotland would continue to be governed by the provisions of the 2016 Act, but no regulations would be made. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Costs</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The 2016 Act clearly sets out the will of parliament to reform burial legislation and regulations are required to give effect to many of those provisions. The “do nothing” option would not fulfil that intention.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>This option would neglect some of the key recommendations from the Burial and Cremation Review Group and the Burial Regulations Working Group ('BRWG'). </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>There is a clear and long-standing expectation from stakeholders and the public that changes will be made in this important area of body disposal, evidenced by the support shown in the public consultation.     </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Whilst the intention is to have a Burial Code of Practice in future, without burial regulations, there are currently no provisions against which Inspectors of Burial could inspect.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Opportunities for improvement could be lost. The Senior Inspector of Burial, Cremation and Funeral Directors has acknowledged improvements made following the Cremation (Scotland) Regulations 2019 and suggests similar benefits could be achieved for burial.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Benefits</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Little to no impact on the operation of burial authorities and no additional resources required.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_16">
        <heading><b>Not recommended.</b></heading>
        <content />
      </section>
      <section eId="section_17">
        <heading><b>Option B – Voluntary/ self-regulation by business</b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>One of the key aims of the burial regulations is to bring consistency across Scotland, by setting out clear processes and improved record-keeping and to promote a common understanding of good practice. Under Option B, burial authorities would be largely self-regulated. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Costs</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>As with option A, without burial regulations, Inspectors of Burial would have limited legal provision against which to inspect and whilst they could make recommended improvements, they would be limited in their ability to take enforcement action for non-compliance. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>A voluntary scheme would set burial apart from other areas of the funeral sector – cremation authorities and funeral directors – where regulations and standards are either in place or are upcoming. A departure from this would be at odds with the wider intentions of the inspection regime. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>If burial application forms and information to be included in burial registers were not made statutory, burial authorities could choose not to use them, which means the current inconsistency of several different forms being used by burial authorities could continue.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Benefits:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Self-regulation is more flexible than regulations.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Linked to the above, non-statutory application forms would provide flexibility for amendments as they are fully tested and implemented.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_18">
        <heading><b>Not recommended</b>.</heading>
        <content />
      </section>
      <section eId="section_19">
        <heading><b>Option C – Regulation of burial by legislation, implemented at the same time</b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Under option C, a comprehensive package of secondary legislation, covering all aspects of the burial sector regulated by the 2016 Act, would be developed and considered by Parliament at the same time. This would include regulations for burial management, applications and registers, exhumation, private burial and restoration of lairs. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Costs:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Introducing multiple sets of regulation at once, with fundamental changes to exhumation and new procedures for private burial and restoration of lairs at the same time as these burial regulations could be overly burdensome on business and the third sector.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Benefits:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>By developing regulations, as opposed to voluntary guidance, burial authorities must comply with important requirements.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Regulations provide a baseline against which burial authorities can be inspected. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Progressing all burial regulations as a full package (rather than in stages), recognises the interaction and overlap between different parts of burial regulation, enabling them to be developed holistically. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_20">
        <heading><b>Not recommended</b>.</heading>
        <content />
      </section>
      <section eId="section_21">
        <heading><b>Option D – Regulation of burial by legislation, implemented in stages   </b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Option D is the same as Option C but rather than having a comprehensive package of secondary legislation that is laid before Parliament at the same time, we would prioritise and regulate some areas first (burial management, applications and registers) and postpone other aspects (exhumation, private burial and restoration of lairs) to a later date.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Costs:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Limits the holistic overview of the different sets of burial regulations and the way they interact.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Benefits: </heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>As with option C, by developing regulations, as opposed to voluntary self-regulation, we can ensure that burial authorities are meeting important requirements and provide a baseline against which authorities can be inspected. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>By splitting the regulations and implementing in stages, each set of regulations could be considered separately with the full attention, focus and review of each discrete part by policy officials and working group members.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Focussing on management, applications and registers first gives stakeholders the opportunity to imbed the new requirements into their daily practice before further regulation is introduced. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Splitting the burial regulations by topic is more accessible as users of each set of regulations will differ, making it easier for people to access only the information relevant to them in their circumstances. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Postponing private burial, exhumation and reuse of lairs is appropriate given their novelty and offers further opportunities for engagement as the policies are refined.  </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_22">
        <heading>recommended.</heading>
        <content>
          <p>Option D is <b>recommended. </b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_23">
        <heading><b>Option E - Exemptions for small burial authorities </b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>An extension to Option C or D but with consideration given to whether there should be exemptions or flexibilities for smaller and/or volunteer burial authorities. Please see section 3.1 for more information. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Costs</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Inappropriate and contradictory to objectives to require lesser standards or different procedures from small burial authorities. All members of the public should be able to expect the same robust processes and dignified level of service, regardless of who is managing the burial ground.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>This option would lead to variation across different burial authorities, contrary to the overall intentions of the burial regulations. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Exempting small burial authorities from burial regulations is, by extension, exempting these authorities from meeting the requirements expected as part of the wider inspection programme. This means there would be no or limited rules or standards against which they could be inspected.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>It would be difficult to identify and describe which burial authorities would benefit from a lesser degree of regulation. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Benefits</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>No risk of disincentivising volunteers due to additional duties.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><b>Not recommended.</b> The requirements in the burial regulations have been developed with the various types of burial authority in mind and are not considered to be difficult to achieve. Where the burial regulations do require the dedication of some resource - e.g. the creation of a management plan – consultation feedback has informed decisions around the content of the plans and length of time required to prepare them so as not to impose a disproportionate burden. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>1.5</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Sectors and groups affected</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>A.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Burial Authorities </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The main sector affected by the burial regulations is burial authorities. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The vast majority of burial grounds in Scotland are managed by local authorities, of which there are 32. However, unlike the Burial Grounds (Scotland) Act 1855 which extended to local authority burial authorities only, the 2016 Act and its regulations apply equally to burial authorities that are local authorities, private companies, community groups, volunteer societies and non-departmental public bodies. The exact number of burial authorities in Scotland is unknown but the expectation is that information about burial authorities will improve with the introduction of an inspection register to maintain a list of burial authorities, cremation authorities and funeral directors under the separate, but related Burial and Cremation (Inspection) (Scotland) Regulations 2025 (see inspection BRIA).  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>There is a large variation between local authority burial authorities in regards to scale, geography and service provision. The Scottish islands, for example, face the unique challenge of managing burial grounds which span across many inhabited islands. Glasgow City Council services a population of around 620,700<authorialNote marker="2"><p> Scotland’s Census, 2022 - Scotland's Census 2022 - Rounded population estimates | Scotland's Census (scotlandscensus.gov.uk) - https://www.scotlandscensus.gov.uk/2022-results/scotland-s-census-2022-rounded-population-estimates/</p></authorialNote> with 32 burial grounds, 8 of which are open for burials<authorialNote marker="3"><p> G. Gillespie (11 June 2024), <i>Environment and Liveable Neighbourhoods City Policy Committee</i>, Glasgow City Council - https://onlineservices.glasgow.gov.uk/councillorsandcommittees/viewSelectedDocument.asp?c=P62AFQDN81ZL0GUTDX.</p></authorialNote>.  The authority itself covers an area of an estimated 170 km².  For comparison, Highland Council services a population of around 235,400 with 268 burial grounds, 147 of which are in use and situated across an estimated 25,000 km² area.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <num>B.</num>
          <content>
            <p> Funeral Directors</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Funeral directors have a key role in supporting and guiding families through the process of arranging a funeral. They will need to be aware of the changes made by the burial regulations to enable them to make the appropriate arrangements for burial, if that is the option chosen. An example of this will be advising families on the correct use of the new burial application forms. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_24">
        <num><b>2.</b></num>
        <heading>Section 2 Engagement and information gathering</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Section 2: Engagement and information gathering</b></p>
        </intro>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_25">
        <heading>Engagement approach</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Engagement to date has taken the form of working groups, focussed face to face meetings, online Microsoft Teams meetings, email exchanges and formal public consultation. Existing forums and cross-policy collaboration were utilised where possible and engagement has been an ongoing process through the development of the burial regulations.  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_26">
        <heading>Within Government</heading>
        <level>
          <heading>The Burial, Cremation, Anatomy and Death Certification Team (“the team”) has engaged extensively with various divisions within the Scottish Government (SG), wider ministerial departments, other UK nations and relevant Government agencies and public bodies. This includes:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>SG Faith and Belief Policy Team, for assistance in reaching relevant stakeholders on all aspects of the burial regulations;</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service (COPFS), particularly in relation to authorisation prior to burial;</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Scottish Courts and Tribunal Service (SCTS);</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Scottish Environmental Protection Agency (SEPA) and the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) in relation to burial hazards;</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Historic Environment Scotland (HES), in relation to management of historic headstones.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The team also engaged with other UK nations in relation to cross-border death certification and registration requirements. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Engagement has taken place with the Senior Inspector of Burial, Cremation and Funeral Directors. The Inspector has been inspecting cremation authorities since 2015 and since there is considerable overlap on many of the administrative aspects of the burial and cremation regulations, feedback from the implementation of the Cremation (Scotland) Regulations 2019 was key to assessing the benefits of introducing similar requirements for burial or whether any lessons were learned for things to be done differently. Questions were specifically asked on:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Cremation management plans </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Statutory application forms </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Fifty year retention period for application forms </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Who can apply for a cremation </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Cremation registers.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Inspector’s comments are considered as part of the options assessment in the Annex.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_27">
        <heading>Public Consultation</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Scottish Government undertook a full public consultation on its proposals for the burial regulations between August and November 2023. The consultation consisted of 47 consultation questions with an additional 8 impact assessment questions, one of which was specifically aimed at understanding the impact the burial regulations may have on businesses. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p>There were 59 responses. Of these, 37 (63%) were submitted on behalf of an organisation, and 22 (37%) were from individuals. Of those who identified as ‘individuals’, the majority (18.82%) said they did not work in the funeral sector. Organisation respondents were asked to identify which organisation they were responding on behalf of and the type of work the organisation was involved in. This is shown in the table.</p>
            <table uk:widths="1.38in 2.53in 0.98in 1.15in">
              <tr>
                <td style="background-color:#E7E6E6;vertical-align:middle">
                  <p><span style="background-color:#E7E6E6"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Responding as Individual or on behalf of Organisation</b></span></span></p>
                </td>
                <td style="background-color:#E7E6E6;vertical-align:middle">
                  <p><span style="background-color:#E7E6E6"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Subcategory of employment/organisation</b></span></span></p>
                </td>
                <td style="background-color:#E7E6E6;vertical-align:middle">
                  <p><span style="background-color:#E7E6E6"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Number of responses</b></span></span></p>
                </td>
                <td style="background-color:#E7E6E6;vertical-align:middle">
                  <p><span style="background-color:#E7E6E6"><span style="color:#000000"><b>Percentage of all respondents (n= 59)</b></span></span></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td style="vertical-align:middle" rowspan="6">
                  <p><span style="color:#000000">Individual</span></p>
                </td>
