              <p><span style="color:#333333">Orkney Islands Council</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num><span style="color:#333333">•</span></num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#333333">Scottish Bereavement Benchmarking Group (SBBG)</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num><span style="color:#333333">•</span></num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#333333">Shetland Islands Council</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num><span style="color:#333333">•</span></num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#333333">South Lanarkshire Council</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Minutes of the BRWG meetings are available at: Burial Regulations Working Group - gov.scot (www.gov.scot) and the discussions informed the proposals set out in the consultation and ongoing drafting of the burial regulations. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>In addition to the BRWG, the Scottish Government officials hosted and/or attended five events during the period of public consultation (25 August – 17 November 2023) to present the proposals being consulted on and to give attendees the opportunity to ask any questions they had on the consultations. These were:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Federation of Burial and Cremation Authorities (FBCA) in person (Scottish Sub-Committee Meeting) on 28 September 2023</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>National Association of Funeral Directors (Scotland Executive) on Teams on 5th October 2023</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#333333">Scottish Bereavement Benchmarking Group (SBBG) consultation meeting on Teams on 24 October 2024</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#333333">Two public consultation events on Teams on 24 October and 2 November 2023</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>In addition, various other focussed meetings and discussions took place on specific topics with:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The Scottish Council of Jewish Communities (ScoJeC) </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Scottish Ahlul Bayt Society (SABS) </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Anatomy Bequest Coordinators </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Scottish Bereavement Benchmarking Group (SBBG)</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Due to the interconnected nature of the various regulations under the 2016 Act, where burial regulations have overlapped with inspection regulations, further discussions have taken place with members of the Inspection Regulations Working Group. An example of this was a focussed discussion on compliance and enforcement of the burial regulations which took place on 15 May 2024. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Burial authorities of all types have been engaged throughout the development of the burial regulations. This includes representation on the BRWG, focussed stakeholder discussion, engagement with faith groups, contribution to the public consultation and ongoing engagement with representative organisations. Engagement has been positive and businesses and local authorities are broadly content with the approach being taken. Those consulted were informed that options presented for discussion were not exhaustive or final and were encouraged to suggest or present their own options. As a result, a number of amendments were examined and included in the draft burial regulations.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_29">
        <num><b>3.</b></num>
        <heading>Section 3 Costs, impacts and benefits</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Section 3: Costs, impacts and benefits</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>3.1</b></num>
          <intro>
            <p><b>Quantified costs to businesses</b></p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>A)</num>
            <content>
              <p>General views </p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p>In relation to business and the third sector, the public consultation specifically asked:</p>
            <block name="embeddedStructure">
              <embeddedStructure>
                <level>
                  <content>
                    <p><b>“Question 54</b> - Do you have any views on the potential impacts of the proposals in this consultation on businesses and the third sector?”</p>
                  </content>
                </level>
              </embeddedStructure>
            </block>
            <p>This question received few comments. Of those who did respond, the majority did not think that the burial regulations would have a negative impact on business. The basic administrative nature of the burial regulations means that many of the intended provisions already fall within the remit of burial authorities but are restated and clarified in legislation. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Two respondents commented on the possibility of the regulatory changes impacting volunteers within small burial authorities, affecting remote or island communities or faith based authorities. The concern was that new duties and commitments may disincentivise volunteers as they would take up additional volunteer time. However, on balance, the impacts are considered to be minimal and proportionate and the new requirements straightforward to comply with. Moreover, measures have been included within the burial regulations to minimise the risk of impact, where possible. For example, the public consultation sought views on what timeframe a burial authority would need in order to comply with certain elements of the burial regulations (e.g. creation of a management plan) to ensure all burial authorities are given adequate opportunity to prepare. The timescales in the updated draft burial regulations reflect those responses. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>One respondent in the public consultation felt that authorities impacted would likely pass additional costs on to the public due to budget pressures. As will be discussed in this section, the burial regulations are not likely to significantly increase costs to businesses.</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>B)</num>
            <content>
              <p> Memorial safety </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The maintenance of headstones is the responsibility of the person who owns the headstone, usually the lair right-holder (the person who has the right to be buried in or decide who is buried in the lair). However, over time and with the historic practice of selling lair rights in perpetuity, maintenance work is often not carried out, because the owner is absent or cannot be traced. This is particularly true for headstones which are old. Burial authorities owe health and safety obligations<authorialNote marker="4"><p> Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974 (as amended) (HSWA1974) and the Occupier's Liability (Scotland) Act 1960.</p></authorialNote> to those who are visiting or working in or near their burial grounds.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations set out some of the measures that burial authorities may take to make memorials safe. The SG guidance on memorial safety is already available to support burial authorities in meeting their health and safety obligations. As set out in the guidance, the method for making memorials safe is at the discretion of the burial authority. Some burial authorities will reinstate the headstone at the authority’s expense, but this will not be a requirement of the burial regulations. Whilst this may have benefits for the purpose of conservation and general aesthetics, placing a duty on burial authorities in this respect is unlikely to be able to be met with full compliance, given existing local authority budgets constraints. Moreover, non-local authority burial authorities, such as volunteer-run groups may not have the resources. For this reason, the Burial and Cremation Review Group did not make such a recommendation and the burial regulations do not impose a duty of repair but rather grant powers to burial authorities to take the steps required to make headstones safe. Important considerations in respect to the historic environment are set out in guidance, with scheduled monuments and listed buildings given specific protection in existing legislation.<authorialNote marker="5"><p> Ancient Monuments and Archaeological Areas Act 1979, Planning (Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas) (Scotland) Act 1997.</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations aim to strike a balance between enabling burial authorities to undertake the required work to make headstones and memorials safe, whilst protecting the property rights of lair right-holders by raising awareness of upcoming inspections and giving an opportunity, where possible, for repairs to be made by those who own the memorial.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Burial Management Regulations require burial authorities to carry out regular, scheduled inspections of headstones and other memorials. The procedures for doing so and the frequency of the scheduled inspections are to be set out in the burial management plan for the burial ground. Burial authorities must notify the public prior to carrying out a scheduled inspection. The notification must include the date of the inspection and state that the burial authority may need to take measures to make headstones or other memorials safe following the inspection, giving examples of what those measures may be. The format and method of notification is not set out in the regulations but some methods are suggested in the Scottish Government Memorial Safety Guidance, such as: social media, signage at burial grounds, local press, etc. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The requirement to notify the public of scheduled inspections does not prevent a burial authority from making direct contact with a lair right-holder. Notification can also be considered in conjunction with the methods of making safe. For example, where a memorial is found to be unsafe it might be cordoned off and signposted and/or methods taken for its temporarily making safe for a set period of time, pending contact with the lair right-holder, before permanent action is taken to make it safe. The requirement to carry out scheduled inspections does not prevent burial authorities from carrying out inspections at other times as needed, nor from taking measures to keep headstones or other memorials safe in the interim.    </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The majority of burial authorities already undertake some form of memorial inspection programme and make memorials safe within existing budgets. The proposed burial regulations do not necessarily add to these maintenance costs and it is clear from ongoing engagement with burial authorities, that the introduction of a clear legal framework is welcomed.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Scottish Government’s Memorial Safety Guidance will be replaced by a Code of Practice in due course. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>For any burial authorities which do not proactively and regularly inspect headstones within their burial grounds, but are now required to do so as a direct result of the introduction of these burial regulations, there may be some financial outlay in relation to public notification, for example, signage. Again, this is not considered to be significant and it is open to burial authorities to decide what methods of publicity to use. </heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>C)</num>
            <content>
              <p>Burial applications </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The new statutory burial application forms will replace the current locally produced forms, whereby each burial authority uses its own forms. This is unlikely to result in significant additional costs to funeral directors or burial authorities. The longest statutory form is 6 pages, which is longer than some of the forms used currently (2 pages) and funeral directors and burial authorities may need to train staff on new procedures, e.g. how to advise families on the completion of the new application forms. The forms have been simplified, where possible, so that they collect specific, required information. Additional information has been taken out of the forms and moved to non-statutory guidance notes which will accompany the forms. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Since the statutory forms will now be used for all burials, it is hoped that that the new forms will, in time, lead to some minor administrative savings through reduced processing time and consistent data entry regardless of which burial authority has supplied the form. The standard forms may assist with funeral director training, as there will be no need to input different information depending on the burial authority chosen by the family. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>The application forms have been split into a number of categories:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF1: Application for burial of the remains of an adult, child or ashes (by individual) </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF2: Application for burial of the remains of a stillborn baby (by individual or health body/authority)</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF3: Application for burial of the remains of following a pregnancy loss (by individual) </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF4: Application for burial of the remains of following a pregnancy loss (by a health authority or body – shared or individual burial)</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF5: Application for the burial of the remains of an adult or child where a local authority is making arrangements under section 87 of the 2016 Act</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF6: Application for burial of body parts following a hospital arranged post mortem examination or whole body/body parts donated for anatomical examination (post Anatomy Act 1984)</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>BF7: Application for burial of body parts donated in Scotland in possession of person licensed under section 3(2) of the Anatomy Act 1984 (pre Anatomy Act 1984 or where origin is unknown)</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Some stakeholders expressed concern over the number of application forms being created with some favouring a single form with relevant sections to be completed as necessary. On balance, a single form approach was considered to be insensitive and could result in a lengthy, complex form. This option was similarly considered and decided-against for the cremation application forms in 2019.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>The five Scottish anatomy schools were consulted on the two new burial application forms specific to donated bodies and anatomical specimens and those consulted welcome the introduction of the forms.</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>D)</num>
            <content>
              <p>Burial registers </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Burial authorities currently already have registers, but the burial regulations introduce prescribed information that must be included in these registers. Burial authorities which currently have electronic registers may need to make some changes to IT software to ensure that the burial register content is updated to reflect the information prescribed in the burial regulations. If some burial authorities do not currently use an electronic system but wish to develop one for the purpose of improved record-keeping, there may be some cost involved in developing an appropriate database. It is unlikely to be complex in nature and the cost is expected to be relatively low.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_30">
        <heading>Other impacts</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>All identified impacts have been addressed throughout the BRIA and no additional unintended consequences have been identified.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_31">
        <heading>Scottish firms’ international competitiveness</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations are unlikely to impact competitiveness within the UK or worldwide. A person is unlikely to choose to be buried outwith Scotland, or within Scotland, based on the changes contained within these burial regulations. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>It is understood that Scottish local authorities and other commercial burial authorities do not operate internationally. Service provision tends to be local and so there is no competition with international businesses not subject to the regulatory changes. Consequently, no impacts have been identified in relation to Scotland’s ability to compete internationally. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>A profile of businesses and sectors affected are set out above under ‘scope’ (para 1.2.3), ‘sectors and groups affected’ (para 1.4) and ‘Business’ (para 2.4). </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_32">
        <heading>Benefits to business</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations aim to improve existing procedures, by replacing current processes with more modern and consistent methods. These are likely to have positive implications for business. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Additional benefits include: </heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Standardisation across many aspects of burial, such as the burial application procedure, registers and approach to tackling unsafe headstones, helps authorities to operate more efficiently and predictably. This could help reduce misunderstandings and disputes. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Streamlined and consistent procedures assist with training of staff and save staff time. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Clear rules on operational procedures, for example in the management plan, reduce ambiguity and increase transparency.</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Enhanced public trust in the standards and services provided by burial authorities. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Compliance with the burial regulations may drive authorities to make further improvements, which will be supported by the development of a Burial Code of Practice. This will benefit bereaved customers and support cross-sector working (e.g. with funeral directors).</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Consultation with burial authorities has produced a broadly positive reaction to the proposals and the progression of regulation in the sector.  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_33">
        <heading>Small businesses impacts</heading>
        <level>
          <heading><span style="color:#333333">As set out above under paragraphs 1.3 (Options (Option E)) and </span>3.1 (Quantified costs to businesses), consideration was given to exempting small or volunteer burial authorities from the burial regulations but was dismissed for a number of reasons:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The burial regulations are not expected to be costly to implement and do not require investment to be made. Therefore, small businesses should not be disadvantaged financially.  </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The burial regulations are not expected to discourage volunteers. Whilst there may be some additional administrative resource required, this is not considered to be significant and sufficient time will be given to implement the requirements and manage the associated tasks. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Whilst the scale of operations may be smaller, the same high level of care and service should be afforded to the deceased and bereaved regardless of the size of the burial authority. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>The burial regulations do not propose to stifle flexibility, but rather to empower burial authorities to efficiently carry out tasks they already undertake. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Any enforcement action by inspectors will be proportionate and graduated in nature and is intended to focus on improvement measures in the first instance. </p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_34">
        <heading>Investment</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The provision of burial services is very much locally determined. The proposed burial regulations do not make Scotland a more, or less, attractive place for global investment.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_35">
        <heading>Workforce and Fair Work</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>There are no identified impacts affecting workforce and these burial regulations will not reduce burial authorities’ ability/ likelihood of paying workers at least the real living wage. There will be a requirement to ensure workers are adequately trained in the use of the equipment they operate and all training recorded. This may encourage burial authorities to explore new training options for staff. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_36">
        <heading>Climate change/ Circular Economy</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Standards for burial authorities are likely to be set out in a future code of practice or guidance – part of this may consider ways in which positive environmental change could be achieved. This is not the subject of this BRIA and will be considered separately. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_37">
        <heading>Competition Assessment</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations are not expected to increase or decrease competition in the burial sector. No barriers to entry are identified e.g. no required investment in infrastructure or inspection or licence fees. Neither do the burial regulations stifle innovation or prevent the adoption of new practices, technologies or business models, where that would bring improvements. The burial regulations apply equally to all types of businesses and as mentioned above, are unlikely to have a disproportionate impact on small burial authorities.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_38">
        <heading>Consumer duty</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Does the policy affect the quality, availability or price of any goods or services in a market?</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>No</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Does the policy affect the essential services market, such as energy or water?</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>No</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The policy does not impact energy or water services but burial is an essential service which many people in Scotland will require at a time of particular vulnerability as a consumer. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Does the policy involve storage or increased use of consumer data?</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The new burial application forms require collection of basic data on applicants and instructions for burial. This is not considered to be much different, or in excess, of the information collected currently.  </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Does the policy increase opportunities for unscrupulous suppliers to target consumers?</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>No</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Does the policy impact the information available to consumers on either goods or services, or their rights in relation to these?</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>New national guidance on all aspects of the burial regulations will be produced. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_39">
        <num><b>4.</b></num>
        <heading>Section 4 Additional implementation considerations</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Section 4: Additional implementation considerations</b></p>
        </intro>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_40">
        <heading>Enforcement, Sanctions And Monitoring</heading>
        <level>
          <heading><span style="color:#333333">The related Inspection Regulations (see separate BRIA) </span>provides a framework for the implementation of a statutory inspection regime to monitor compliance and to take enforcement action, when required. In particular, it sets out details on the following topics:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Powers of Inspectors</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Inspection reports</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Enforcement</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Appeals</p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Statutory inspection and enforcement will ensure the funeral industry (including burial authorities) is fully compliant with the 2016 Act, its regulations and associated statutory codes of practice, which, in turn, will improve industry standards and increase public confidence in the sector. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>There has been extensive engagement on the approach to enforcement. This is set out comprehensively in the BRIA for The Burial and Cremation (Inspection) (Scotland) Regulations 2025, so will not be repeated here. The burial sector is considered to be lower risk than other areas of the funeral industry and so inspection is intended to be lighter-touch and focus on inspecting burial authorities, rather than individual burial grounds. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_41">
        <heading>UK, EU and International Regulatory Alignment and Obligations</heading>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_42">
        <heading>Intra-UK Trade Impacts</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Burial practice and procedure already differs throughout the UK. The burial regulations will not cause further divergence. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The death certification and registration procedures in other UK nations will continue to be respected in Scotland if the deceased is to be repatriated to Scotland for burial. Equivalent certificates to the Scottish Certificate of Registration of Death (Form 14) will be accepted in Scotland and this is made clear on the new burial application form. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_43">
        <heading>International Trade</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Is this measure likely to impact on international trade and investment? </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>No, this measure does not have the potential to affect imports or exports of funeral services; it does not have the potential to affect trade flows with one or more countries; and it does not include different requirements for domestic and foreign businesses. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_44">
        <heading>EU Alignment</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>This measure does not impact the Scottish Government’s commitment to maintain and advance the high standards that Scotland shares with the EU; does not impact access to EU markets for people, goods, and services; and does not have any implications for EU alignment associated with the UK Internal Market Act 2020 or Common Framework agreements.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_45">
        <heading>Legal Aid Impact Test</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations are not anticipated to have any impact on availability of legal aid or possible expenditure from the legal aid fund. Neither do they change an existing procedure or right of appeal.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>If burial authorities are found to be in breach of the new regulations, there is a possibility of individuals consulting with a solicitor. However, that risk is thought to be very low. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_46">
        <heading>Digital impact</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The proposals for the burial regulations have been developed with advancing technology in mind, allowing for digital signatures and the completion and transfer of documentation electronically. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Whilst the new statutory burial application forms may not conform entirely with a very small number of existing burial authority websites, the online form is suitable for the vast majority. Individual websites which are more advanced can be updated to replicate the content of the new forms, if required – with any additional information collected separately.   </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>For those with limited digital accessibility, paper versions of the burial application forms will be available for completion. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_47">
        <heading>Business Forms</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial application forms have been subject to extensive consultation with businesses and authorities. Members of the Burial Regulations Working Group have given direct feedback on the draft forms and suggestions have been incorporated, where possible. The content of the forms was set out in the public consultation and further amendments made based on responses received. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <heading>Wider members of the Public Health Capabilities Division in the Scottish Government were asked to complete a draft form and give feedback on how they found the process. Specifically they were asked:</heading>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#000000">Can you easily understand what the form is asking you to do?</span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#000000">Does it follow a logical sequence? </span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
          <paragraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><span style="color:#000000">Can anything be clarified or improved? </span></p>
            </content>
          </paragraph>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The comments were taken on board as the form was finalised. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Senior Inspector of Burial, Cremation and Funeral Directors has reported that similar forms introduced for cremation in 2019 have been received well by crematorium staff, funeral directors and the public. The Inspector is of the view that burial authorities would welcome the same. Moreover, burial registers in their current form vary across burial authorities in terms of the information that they collect; simplified record-keeping is considered to be beneficial. Within local authorities, burial authorities and cremation authorities are often based within the same department, such as Bereavement Services, therefore consistency in the requirements for both methods of body disposal will be welcomed. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_48">
        <num><b>5.</b></num>
        <heading>Section 5 Next steps and implementation</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Section 5: Next steps and implementation</b></p>
        </intro>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_49">
        <heading>Recommendations/ preferred options</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The results of this BRIA confirm the intention to develop regulations for burial management, applications and registers to bring consistency to the sector and a baseline set of requirements against which authorities can be inspected. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>Development in stages, focussing on management, applications and registers first gives stakeholders the opportunity to imbed the new requirements into their daily practice in stages before changes to private burial, exhumation and re-use of lairs are introduced. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_50">
        <heading>Implementation considerations/ plan</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The burial regulations will be scrutinised by Parliament prior to being issued and coming into force. Some elements of the burial regulations will include a time period for burial authorities to take steps, if they have not already done so, to implement the changes.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>During that time, the Scottish Government will create targeted communications to raise awareness of the new requirements, for example, via the dedicated Funeral Industry News Blog, and will continue to work with stakeholders to assist in their introduction. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_51">
        <heading>Post implementation review</heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>The Scottish Government will keep the burial regulations under review, with a formal review being undertaken within 10 years of the burial regulations coming into force.</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_52">
        <num><b>6.</b></num>
        <heading><b>Declaration and Publication</b></heading>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p>I have read the Business and Regulatory Impact Assessment and I am satisfied that (a) it represents a fair and reasonable view of the expected costs, benefits and impact of the policy, and (b) that the benefits justify the costs. I am satisfied that business impact has been assessed with the support of businesses in Scotland. </p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_53">
        <heading>Signed Jenni Minto</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Signed: Jenni Minto</b></p>
        </intro>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><b>Date:</b> <docDate date="2024-11-12"><b>12 November 2024</b></docDate></p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_54">
        <heading>Minister's name Jenni Minto</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Minister's name: Jenni Minto</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_55">
        <heading>Minister's title Minister for Public Health and Women’s Health</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Minister's title: Minister for Public Health and Women’s Health</b></p>
        </intro>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><b>Scottish Government Contact point:</b> Rachael Thomson – Burial, Cremation, Anatomy and Death Certification Team</p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_56">
        <heading>ANNEX</heading>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <blockContainer>
              <num><b>7.</b></num>
              <p><b>Policy options assessment</b></p>
            </blockContainer>
            <p><b>Table 1 </b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.97in 1.77in 3.15in 2.8in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Policy </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Option </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Costs </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Benefits </b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Management plan </b></p>
                  <p>(A document which sets out how a burial authority manages it’s burial grounds and contains information such as procedures for keeping burial grounds well maintained and dealing with an unexpected rise in the number of burials).</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – do nothing, no requirement for a management plan. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Loss of opportunity to set out how burial authorities manage their burial grounds. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Loss of opportunity to create consistency across burial and cremation authorities. Cremation management plans became a requirement under the Cremation (Scotland) Regulations 2019. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No resource implications for burial authorities to create a plan and carry out annual reviews. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Options 2 – require a management plan.</p>
                  <p><b>Recommended. </b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Requires burial authorities to dedicate time and resource to the development of the plan and its annual review. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Consistency across burial and cremation authorities and benefits of transparency in relation to burial ground management. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Not considered to be difficult to produce. Minimum information for inclusion will be prescribed, with the option for burial authorities to add more information if they wish.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>The Senior Inspector of Burial, Cremation and Funeral Directors advises that management plans (in the cremation context) are deemed to be of value to staff and a single source of information. It is of particular benefit when new members of staff are appointed. No issues noted about preparation of the plans. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Approach agreed with BRWG.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>General provisions for burial management and scope of burial authority powers </b></p>
                  <p>(In relation to general maintenance of walls and structures, layout and embellishment, access, steps to make headstones and memorials safe, levelling surfaces of lairs, repositioning kerbs, railing, plants).</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – Do nothing – do not set out burial authority powers </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Does not provide clarity on the powers that burial authorities have to manage and maintain their burial grounds. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Does not implement the recommendation of the Burial and Cremation Review Group or the BRWG. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No clear benefits. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – places a duty on burial authorities to keep burial grounds in good order, to inspect headstones and sets out the powers of burial authorities to manage their burial grounds in regulation. </p>
                  <p><b>Recommended.</b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Minor financial outlay in relation to public notification for burial authorities who do not currently raise awareness of memorial inspection programmes. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Puts powers of maintenance onto a statutory footing, giving reassurance and clarity to burial authorities. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Regulations provide flexibility in relation to methods of awareness raising, frequency of inspections  and methods of making headstones safe.</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 3 – an extension of option 2 but places duties on burial authorities to carry out repairs to an expected standard.  </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Potential financial impact, especially if a burial authority was required to repair headstones after making them safe. Due to rising costs in relation to memorial repair, this would limit an authority’s ability to manage and prioritise their funding across wider areas of responsibility and could lead to costs being passed onto the public. For example, local authorities are increasingly likely to prioritise investment to ensure active burial grounds are safe and can remain open. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Discussed in BRIA to the Bill and consensus was that burial regulations should not require burial authorities to carry out activity not already undertaken. Many burial authorities would not be able to meet the requirements. For this reason, the burial and cremation review group did not make a recommendation in this regard and the BRWG reiterated this in discussions. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Setting standards in relation to burial grounds is considered more appropriate as part of the development of the Burial Code of Practice as provided for in s21 of the 2016 Act, rather than in regulations. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Higher standards of management and maintenance. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 4 – Guidance only </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>The existing guidance applies only to local authority burial authorities.</p>
                  <p>It is not enforceable if a burial authority does not follow guidance.  </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No identified benefits. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Criminal offences </b></p>
                  <p>(the 2016 Act allows the burial regulations to make specific offences in relation to burial grounds that are not otherwise set out in the 2016 Act)</p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – do nothing</p>
                  <p><b>Recommended.</b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No costs identified. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Relevant activities are already criminalised under existing legislation. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Local authorities already have the authority, through the Civic Government (Scotland) Act 1982, to create and enforce Management Rules regulating the use of and conduct of persons within burial grounds.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Privately-owned burial authorities can set their own rules and guidelines.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – create offences</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No benefit, as agreed with the BRWG. Relevant offences already covered by existing legislation. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Difficult to enforce and prosecute. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No benefits identified.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>The depth at which human remains may be buried</b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – set out in regulation </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>BRWG preference was for burial depth to be included in guidance or code of practice as the burial regulations would need to be caveated for factors such as ground condition.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Clear established rule in relation to burial depth. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Majority of stakeholders and 2015 Bill consultees in favour of regulating burial depth. Benefits include protection from animal ingress.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – set out in code of practice.</p>
                  <p><b>Recommended. </b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No legal requirement for burial depth until a code of practice is developed, leading to continued inconsistent practice. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>As agreed with the BRWG, requirements for burial depth should be included in the Burial Code of Practice.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Faith designation </b></p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – do nothing </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Slight lack of clarity about what a local authority can provide. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Local authorities already provide dedicated areas where these are requested. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – include the power to designate faith areas within burial grounds.</p>
                  <p><b>Recommended. </b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No identified costs. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>A clearly defined power to designate certain areas of burial grounds. This is a power, not a duty, so there will be flexibility to provide for it where there is a local need.</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p>Training requirements </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – do nothing </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Missed opportunity to ensure staff at burial grounds are adequately trained. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>No records against which an inspector can assess level of training. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Status quo – no impact on burial authorities. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – no specific  training qualification specified, but a requirement in the burial regulations to ensure staff are trained in the operation of the equipment relevant to their day to day duties  and a record of such training kept.</p>
                  <p><b>Recommended. </b></p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Minor resource impact for burial authorities which do not currently keep records of training.  </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option supported by the majority in public consultation and generally reflects current practice so will have minor impact. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Records of training will assist inspector when assessing authority. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Opportunity to set out training requirements further in Burial Code of Practice. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Consistency with requirement for cremation authorities. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 3 – specify exact training requirements and qualifications for burial authority staff. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>There is currently no appropriate accredited qualifications, training or CPD available which would cover all types of burial authority therefore it would not be feasible or appropriate to stipulate certified training programmes. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Training within small or volunteer run burial authorities is often informal in-house or ‘on the job’ training and these burial authorities may not have the resources to pay for training courses. It may not be appropriate to expect volunteers and part-time staff to cover costs themselves. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>If there did exist an adequate accredited training programme, could lead to higher standard of service. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Burial application forms and registers</b> (new standardised forms) </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – do nothing </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Loss of opportunity to improve and standardise the information collected in burial application forms and registers. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Continued lack of consistency. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Status quo maintained. No resource implications for burial authorities.</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – create standardised but non-statutory forms and registers. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Burial authorities could choose not to use the forms, leading to continued ad-hoc and outdated procedures in some burial authorities. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Cost of producing new forms.</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>More flexibility in making amendments to the forms. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 3 – create statutory forms and registers.  </p>
                  <p><b>Recommended. </b></p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>More difficult to amend and less flexibility for burial authorities; they will need to replace their own forms with a standard form. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Incompatibility with some existing digital platforms.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Cost of producing new forms.</p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Standardisation and improvement in the information to be collected and recorded.  </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Not considered difficult or time-consuming to complete new application.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Requiring an application provides a record of who applied for the burial  and evidence of eligibility to make arrangements.  </p>
                  <p>Bereavement Services are often based at a crematorium and perform the role of both burial and cremation authority – alignment likely to be welcomed.</p>
                  <p> </p>
                  <p>The Senior Inspector of Burial, Cremation and Funeral Directors advises that standardised forms (in the cremation context) are deemed to be of value to staff both at the crematorium and funeral directors. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Majority support in consultation for proposed register requirements content. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Slight administrative saving and ease of staff training by using the same form anywhere in Scotland. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p><b>Burial of ashes</b></p>
                  <p>(accompanying documentation)</p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 1 – no requirements in regulation </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No evidence of whose ashes are being buried. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Ad hoc and inconsistent practice across Scotland. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>No impact on burial authorities. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 2 – Cremation certificate or register extract </p>
                  <p><b>Recommended (but with caveat for ashes from abroad). </b></p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>May not be available for ashes from abroad. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Evidences that a cremation has taken place and provides some evidence of the identity of the deceased.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Majority support from consultees/ suggestion that a cremation certificate or copy is easily obtainable.</p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Reflects current practice for most burial authorities. </p>
                  <p />
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Option 3 – Cremation certificate, or Certificate of Registration of Death (Form 14) or death register extract. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>A Form 14 or death register extract only shows that someone has died but does not evidence that a cremation has taken place. </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p>Alternative route to show evidence of the identity of the deceased if cremation certificate lost. </p>
                  <p />
                  <p>Not fully supported by consultees. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
    </mainBody>
  </doc>
</akomaNtoso>
